{{Coord|43|44|4.74|N|7|25|16.8|E|scale:1563_type:landmark_region:MC|display=title}} {{Infobox Grand Prix race report | Type = F1 | Country = Monaco | Grand Prix = Monaco | Date = 3 June | Year = 1973 | Image = Circuit de Monaco 1973.png | Caption = Circuit de Monaco | Official name = XXXI [[Monaco Grand Prix|Grand Prix de Monaco]] | Location = [[Monte Carlo]], Monaco | Course = Street circuit | Course_km = 3.278 | Course_mi = 2.037 | Distance_laps = 78 | Distance_km = 255.684 | Distance_mi = 158.886 | Pole_Driver = [[Jackie Stewart]] | Pole_Team = [[Tyrrell Racing|Tyrrell]]-[[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] | Pole_Country = United Kingdom | Pole_Time = 1:27.5 | Fast_Driver = [[Emerson Fittipaldi]] | Fast_Team = [[Team Lotus|Lotus]]-[[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] | Fast_Country = Brazil | Fast_Time = 1:28.1 | Fast_Lap = 78 | First_Driver = [[Jackie Stewart]] | First_Team = [[Tyrrell Racing|Tyrrell]]-[[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] | First_Country = United Kingdom | Second_Driver = [[Emerson Fittipaldi]] | Second_Team = [[Team Lotus|Lotus]]-[[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] | Second_Country = Brazil | Third_Driver = [[Ronnie Peterson]] | Third_Team = [[Team Lotus|Lotus]]-[[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] | Third_Country = Sweden }} The '''1973 Monaco Grand Prix''' was a [[Formula One]] motor race held at [[Circuit de Monaco|Monaco]] on 3 June 1973. It was race 6 of 15 in both the [[1973 World Championship of Drivers]] and the [[1973 International Cup for Formula One Manufacturers]].
The race was held on a heavily revised circuit, with a longer tunnel, a new section of track around the new swimming pool on the harbour front, and the Gasworks hairpin replaced by the Rascasse and Antony Noghès corners, the latter named after the [[Antony Noghès|founder of the race]]. The pits were also moved back to the start-finish straight, on a wider pit lane.
The 78-lap race was won from [[pole position]] by Scotland's [[Jackie Stewart]], driving a [[Tyrrell 006|Tyrrell]]-[[Ford Motor Company|Ford]]. In the process, Stewart equalled the record of 25 Grand Prix victories set by his friend [[Jim Clark]]. Brazil's [[Emerson Fittipaldi]] finished second in a [[Lotus 72|Lotus]]-Ford, with Swedish teammate [[Ronnie Peterson]] third.
This was the first race for future World Champion [[James Hunt]], driving a [[March Engineering|March]]-Ford entered by [[Hesketh Racing]]. Hunt suffered an engine failure in the closing stages of the race, but was classified ninth.
