{{Politics of Comoros}}

The '''Comorian Party for Democracy and Progress''' ({{lang-fr|Parti Comrorien pour la Démocratie et le Progrès}}, PCDP) was a political party in the [[Comoros]].

==History==
Led by [[Ali Mroudjaé]], the PCDP went into opposition in November 1991. The party won three seats in the [[Comorian legislative election, 1992|1992 parliamentary elections]].<ref>[http://www.ipu.org/parline-e/reports/arc/2069_92.htm Elections held in 1992] IPU</ref> However, it was reduced to a single seat in the [[Comorian legislative election, 1993|early elections]] the following year.

Mroudjaé was the party's candidate for the [[Comorian presidential election, 2002|2002 presidential elections]], finishing eighth out of nine candidates with 4% of the vote. Prior to the [[Comorian legislative election, 2004|2004 parliamentary elections]] the RND joined the [[Camp of the Autonomous Islands]] alliance, which was opposed to Azali. The alliance won 12 of the 18 elected seats  and all 15 of the indirectly-elected seats.

The party nominated Loutfi Soulaimane as its candidate for the [[Comorian presidential election, 2006|2006 presidential elections]]. He received only 2% of the vote, finishing eleventh in a field of 13 candidates.

