{{multiple issues| {{cleanup reorganize|date=October 2013}} {{context|date=October 2013}} {{lead rewrite|date=October 2013}}{{notability|Music|date=October 2013}} {{unreferenced|date=October 2013}} }} {{Infobox song contest entry | song = {{flagicon|Switzerland}} "Giorgio" | image = [[File:Eurovision Song Contest 1958 - Lys Assia.png|260px]] | caption = | year = 1958 | country = Switzerland | artist = [[Lys Assia]] | as = | with = | language = | languages = [[German language|German]], [[Italian language|Italian]] | composer = [[Paul Burkhard]] | lyricist = Fridolin Tschudi | conductor = [[Paul Burkhard]] | place = 2nd | points = 24 | lyrics = [http://www.diggiloo.net/?1958ch from Diggiloo thrush] | prev = L'enfant que j'étais | prev_link = L'enfant que j'étais | next = Irgendwoher | next_link = Irgendwoher }}
'''"Giorgio"''' was the [[Switzerland|Swiss]] entrant to the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1958]], held in [[Hilversum]], the [[Netherlands]]. It was performed in [[German language|German]] and [[Italian language|Italian]]. It was the first song to be performed in more than one language in the Eurovision Song Contest.
The song was performed by [[Lys Assia]], winner for Switzerland at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1956|1956 contest]], and was composed by [[Paul Burkhard]] and [[Fridolin Tschudi]].
On the night of the contest, the song was performed 10th (last), following [[Austria]]'s [[Liane Augustin]] with "[[Die ganze Welt braucht Liebe]]". At the close of the voting, Assia had received 24 points, placing second behind [[France]]'s [[André Claveau]].
It was succeeded as [[Switzerland in the Eurovision Song Contest|Swiss representative]] at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1959|1959 contest]] by [[Christa Williams]] with "[[Irgendwoher]]".
