{{For|the Alliance for Financial Inclusion's Global Policy Forum|AFI Global Policy Forum}}

'''Global Policy Forum''' ('''GPF'''), founded in 1993, is an organization seeking to promote accountability of [[international organization]]s such as the [[United Nations]] and strengthen [[international law]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Understanding The Face of Globalization: Online Internet Guide|publisher=[[University of Wisconsin–Madison]]|url=http://www.uwm.edu/Dept/CIE/Resources/globalization/globalgen.html|accessdate=2008-11-14}}</ref>

Founding Executive Director [[James A. Paul|James Paul]] and his team have written a number of prominent policy papers on such topics as global taxes, [[United Nations Security Council|Security Council]] reform, the world food/hunger crisis, and problems of development aid. GPF's website has collections of analyses on subjects such as [[Reform of the United Nations|UN reform]], [[international development]], [[NGO]]s, and [[globalization]].  

GPF's stated mission is to:
* Monitor policy making at the United Nations;
* Promote accountability of global decisions;
* Educate and mobilize for global citizen participation;
* Advocate on vital issues of international peace and justice.

GPF has [[consultative status]] at the [[United Nations]]. It convenes the NGO Working Group on the [[United Nations Security Council|Security Council]] about 40 times per year, usually meeting with Security Council Ambassadors and occasionally with senior UN Secretariat officials or Foreign Ministers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Reference Reports and Materials|publisher=[[United Nations]]|url=https://www.un.org/reform/civilsociety/sc.shtml|accessdate=2008-11-14}}</ref> Its primary office is in [[New York City|New York]], located in the [[United Nations Headquarters|United Nations Plaza]]. Since September 2004 it has had a branch based in [[Bonn]], [[Germany]], called Global Policy Forum Europe.

