{{Expand Dutch|Janhagel|date=June 2016}}
'''Janhagel''' or '''Jan Hagel''' is a typical [[Dutch cuisine|Dutch]] kind of [[cookie]]. It is a rectangular, brittle cookie, covered with [[granulated sugar]] (the 'hagel') and possibly [[almond]] shavings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://farmersalmanac.com/food/2015/12/21/the-history-of-jan-hagels/|title=The History Of Jan Hagels, The Traditional Dutch Christmas Cookies |date=21 December 2015|publisher=[[Farmers' Almanac]]}}</ref> It's an old Dutch specialty.
Many people know Jan Hagel as small cookies with [[anise sugar]] on it, but there is also another form of Jan Hagel, a taai-taai-like cake with anise taste. This cake is still baked by Bakery Kok.
Previously, this cake was known as 'Strontboen' Jan Hagel. Because when farmers had cleaned the stable the staff ate Jan Hagel.
== See also == * [[Pain à la grecque]]
