The '''Namibia Economic Policy Research Unit''' (NEPRU) was a [[Namibia|Namibian]] [[non-governmental organization]] whose mission was "to support Namibia's national development goals by providing [[economic policy]] advice, conducting economic research and building economic research capacity", according to its website which is now offline.<ref>[http://www.nepru.org.na/ NEPRU: Home<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081116000249/http://www.nepru.org.na/ |date=2008-11-16 }}</ref> NEPRU, which was established in 1990 when Namibia attained [[Namibian independence|independence]], closed down in 2011 after a drawn-out [[financial crisis]].<ref>[http://www.namibian.com.na/index.php?id=28&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=76573&no_cache=1 The Namibian, 1 Nov 2011]</ref> During its 20 years of existence, it generated a wide range of consultancy reports and was funded through "income from commissioned research and financial as well as technical support from International Cooperation partners".<ref>[http://www.nepru.org.na/index.php?id=6 NEPRU: About Us<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

