{{Infobox musical artist <!-- For individuals; see Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians --> | name = Noroc | image = Stamp of Moldova md090cvs.jpg | caption = | image_size = | background = group_or_band | alias = Contemporanul | origin = [[Chişinău]] | instrument = | genre = | occupation = | years_active = | label = | associated_acts = | website = }}
'''Noroc''' is a [[music]] [[Band (music)|group]] from [[Moldova]], created in 1967 by [[Mihai Dolgan]].
==History== "Noroc" became very popular in the [[USSR]]<ref>{{ro icon}} Fără Mihai Dolgan, ''Timpul'', March 20, 2008</ref><ref name=kp>{{cite web|url=http://old.kp.md/freshissue/life/259763/|script-title=ru:Группе "Норок" - 40 лет!|publisher=Комсомольская Правда|accessdate=2009-05-23|language=ru}}</ref> after the release of their first album in 1968 which included the following songs: * "De ce plâng chitarele" (music: Mihai Dolgan; lyrics: [[Grigore Singurel|Efim Crimerman]]) * "Cântă un artist" (music: Mihai Dolgan; lyrics: Efim Crimerman)
In 1970, "Noroc" won the "public sympathy" prize at the "Bratislava Lyra" festival .<ref name=tiuk>{{cite web|url=http://www.tiuk.reea.net/9/muzon.html|title=De la naştere la "Noroc"|accessdate=2009-05-23|language=ro}}</ref> Later the same year, after a tour of the Ukraine, "Noroc" was banned as a result of a direct order by [[Ivan Bodiul]],<ref name=bbc>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/romanian/moldova/story/2007/10/071025_time_out.shtml|title=TIME OUT: Istoria legendarei formaţii "Noroc"|publisher=BBC Romanian|language=ro}}</ref> Chief Secretary of the [[Communist Party of Moldova|Communist Party]] of the [[Moldavian Soviet Socialist Republic]], due to "lack of discipline", "promotion of artistic values of poor quality", and "lack of healthy ideological orientation".<ref name="tiuk" /> Between the years 1974-1985 the band was reorganized by Mihai Dolgan under the name "Contemporanul". After 1985, "Contemporanul" reverted to the original name "Noroc". Since 1989 up to Mihai Dolgan's death in 2008, "Noroc"'s permanent vocalists were: Lidia Botezatu, Radu Dolgan, Mihai Dolgan.
The word "noroc" means "good luck" in the [[Romanian language]]. This word is also used as a greeting. "Noroc" is also said while toasting (the Romanian equivalent of "cheers").
