{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}} {{Use British English|date=November 2016}} {{Infobox book | italic title = <!--(see above)--> | name = | image = The_Seafarers_(novel).png | image_size = | alt = | caption = Cover of the first publication (2002) | author = [[Nevil Shute]] | audio_read_by = | title_orig = | orig_lang_code = | title_working = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = Brooke Steiger | country = | language = English | series = | release_number = | subject = | genre = | set_in = | publisher = The Paper Tiger, Inc. (Creskill, New Jersey) | publisher2 = | pub_date = 2002 | english_pub_date = | published = | media_type = | pages = | awards = | isbn = 1-889439-32-0 | isbn_note = | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | native_wikisource = | wikisource = | notes = | exclude_cover = | website = {{URL|http://www.papertig.com/shute.htm}} }} '''''The Seafarers''''' is a [[novella]] by [[Nevil Shute]], written in the late 1940s but unpublished until 2002.
==Background== Shute wrote the first draft of ''The Seafarers'' in 1946–47, and rewrote it shortly afterwards, but he apparently put it aside. In 1948 he rewrote it again as ''Blind Understanding'' (unpublished), but left that manuscript incomplete. Some of the themes in ''The Seafarers'' and ''Blind Understanding'' emerged later in ''[[Requiem for a Wren]]'', published in 1955.<ref>{{cite book |contributor-last=Telfair |contributor-first=Dan |contribution=Foreword |last=Shute |first=Nevil |authorlink=Nevil Shute |title=The Seafarers |publisher=The Paper Tiger, Inc. |date=2002 |isbn=1-889439-32-0 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/The_Seafarers.html?id=fMgUPQAACAAJ}}</ref>
==Plot== At the end of [[World War II]], at [[Portland Harbour]], [[Lieutenant (Royal Navy)|Lieutenant]] Donald Wolfe is supervising the [[Ship decommissioning|decommissioning]] of the [[motor torpedo boat]] which he commanded with distinction during the war. The dockyard workers are brought to his vessel in a boat driven by [[Leading Wren]] Jean Porter.<ref>Note: in ''Blind Understanding'' the heroine is Janet Payne; in ''Requiem For A Wren'' she is Janet Prentice alias Jessie Proctor.</ref> Each is impressed by the other's practical, no-nonsense approach to their work and they become friends. They part when Donald leaves Portland to lay up his disarmed MTB. After both are [[Demobilisation|demobilised]] they meet again and Donald discovers that the girl he knew as a boatwoman comes from a well-off family whose social environment is very different from his own. He realises that although they both wish to marry each other, the marriage could not work. They go their separate ways, he to work in an insurance office and she (for something to do, rather than for the money) to learn to be a [[shorthand typist]].
But both are dissatisfied with their lives on land and each separately returns to the sea, he to deliver a yacht to England across the Atlantic from [[Newfoundland]] and she to deliver a yacht to England from [[Guernsey]]. Eventually they meet again on the [[River Hamble|Hamble]] and set up a partnerhip – Wolfe and Porter – to work on boats. They realise that now they can marry, despite her wealthy background, because they earn enough to "keep her in the style she's accustomed to. ... [[Gumboots]] and dirty clothes, and [[Primus stove]]s, and rough food, and salt water. Not the [[Savoy Hotel]]."
